<br>
You can find jobs for gaijins in Japan at www.GaijinPot.com and specifically ENGLISH TEACHING jobs at www.OhayoSensei.com .<br>
<br>
About your CHOICE of jobs:  70% of all foreigners in Japan, who come from English-speaking countries, are professional English teachers.  No matter what you want to become, your best bet to get money in your pocket is to teach English.  It helps ALOT if you arrive with a work-visa, a college degree (in ANYTHING) or a faked college degree, and even MORE if you've got a certification in teachign English as a Foreign Language.  (There are cheap $1,000/1-month courses in that kinda thing .  Do a google search, and I'm sure you can find a school for that in Hawaii. )<br>
<br>
Remember that to WORK in Japan, you have to prove that you can do the work better than a Japanese guy.  Clearly, then, &quot;English teaching&quot; is a safe bet, but &quot;artist&quot; is darned-near impossible.  Take the case of my friend, a 7th generation European blacksmith and lifetime professional:  Despite being a world-class artist with credentials up the wazoo, and being from Holland (a non-English-speaking country), he spent his first 3 years in Japan as an ENGLISH TEACHER, and filing something like 3 kilograms of paperwork to finally, finally get his art-professional work visa.<br>
<br>
The $ for teaching English is phenomenal.  At a commercial conversation school (Eikaiwa) that can give you a visa, you typically get $2000 a month (250,000 yen).  For private lessons that you do on your own, you can get $25 to $50 (3000 to 6000 yen) per hour.  Big, easy $ like that is why so many foreigners in Japan are English teachers.  <br>
<br>
Big English schools like NOVA and AEON and GEOS do their interviewing and hiring overseas.  They're crap to work for, but once you have a work visa, you can change employers in Japan.  Most other schools won't hire you unless you do the interview in Japan, and ALREADY have a work visa, which is a bit of a catch-22... so instead, hire on with one of the big (crappy) companies and then trade up.  Or, if can get it, grab one of the JET (Japan English Teaching) jobs, where you teach English at a public high school.  I'ts 40 % more money per month than regular teachers' jobs, and it's often dead-simple work.<br>
<br>
You could try getting a student-visa, and working as a private English teacher on the side (for the big $).  If it's an art school, maybe they can even set you up with a work-study program so you can get into the pro art scene.  Regular jobs in a Japanese company DO NOT earn you the big bucks for short hours, though.  Japanese &quot;salarymen&quot; &quot;volunteer&quot; evenings and weekends without pay, working late for nothing except to impress their bosses.  And, the Japanese pride themselves on &quot;gaman suri&quot; (enduring crap without complaint&quot;.  The cartoonists' scene is no exception.<br>
<br>
About being a translator in Japan:  Forget it.  Translating is for the cream of the crop...and you're not there, yet.  It's also a crap job, paying little and squeezing yourself into a very uncomfortable role in business negotiations.  Japanese business language and customs are EXTREMELY EXTREMELY finicky, from the way you accept someone's business card to the type of Japanese that you speak.  (Business relations are done in a special, very polite form of Japanese called &quot;keigo&quot; or &quot;Tei-nei go&quot;.  As far as I know, there's no book for foreigners on how to speak Keigo (except for really basic stuff).<br>
<br>
About being a translator in Hawaii:  Different story, there.  There are lots of jobs there where you'll be rewarded for knowing even a little Japanese.  You're competing with lots and LOTS of second-generation immigrants, though, so there are LOTS of top-notch translators.  Set your expectations a little lower, like Japanese sales and tour-guide and airport greeter.  Start out at Kelly temps or any of the other temping agencies, and they'll not only find you work... they'll help you build your skills, too.<br>
You won't earn $ there, though:  expect $10 an hour for almost any entry-level job, and 30% taxes paid on that.  You can get an apartment (expensive), and ride the bus ($15 a month, whadda deal !), but if you're only gonna be there a few months, seriously consider living in one of the HOSTELS, where you can live very cheaply and hang out with tourists.  (I lived in Hawaii for 5 or 6 years, so I speak from alot of experience.)  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=higakun>higakun</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://komplx.com/higan/Page_2/IMAG000.JPG" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/14/03 6:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1227.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://images.warcry.com/image.php?id=4964 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re</span><hr size=1> well i plan on one year. i am not sure if you have ever been to hawaii, but if you haven't it is very much full of japanese culture. in school we actually recited on a regular basis ichi ni san shi go roku shichi hachi ku ju. over and over. domo arigato. and moving back to my home in hawaii will make it very easy for me to learn it quicker. in fact a funny story. when i arrived on the mainland USA i was a little shocked to see spanish on the public signs instead of japanese. its funny because at the airport you will hear a voice on the intercomm in japanaese. but at the same time, it was all around me so much i never paid attention to it. lol but anyway my level is small. i can read hiragana and katakana. more like a hooked on phoenics commercial though lol. and i can recognize over 100 kanji although i may not be able to pronounce them. thats a problem. noone here in