<br>
If not...read on.<br>
=============<br>
Expensive:<br>
<br>
Supermarket stuff is generally the same as America, but NOT including bread, coffee, peanut butter, pizza, and breakfast cereals, which are surprisingly costly.<br>
<br>
MOVIES and BAKERY STUFF are surprisingly expensive... 2 to 3 times what you'd expect to pay in America.<br>
<br>
RENTING AN APARTMENT is generally done through a real-estate agent (fudou-san), but this is phenomenally expensive, and the jerk is not on your side.  Instead, he's the front-man for the landlord, whom you probably won't meet ever.  Also, when you move in, the real-estate agent expects you to give him<br>
a) one month's rent in advance<br>
b) one or two months' rent-worth in security deposit and &quot;tatami flooring refurbishing money&quot; that you very likely won't get back when you move out<br>
and (here's the big BIG shocker)<br>
c) one to two months' rent-worth as a &quot;gift&quot; or commission to him, when you move in.  Gag-koff-koff.<br>
This gift is sometimes called &quot;key-money&quot; in English.  Sorry I can't recall the Japanese name for it.<br>
Your best bet is to quiz Japanese friends, and try to find an apartment that a) doesn't have a real-estate agent and b) doesn't expect &quot;key-money&quot;.  These apartments are bargain-basement deals, but maybe you can get lucky if you go through word-of-mouth.  Keep in mind, though, that many landlords and real estate agents expect foreigners to be smelly, noisy flakes who'll befoul the apartment and leave in the middle of the night owing a month's rent.<br>
<br>
OWNING A CAR or a large-engine motorbike in Japan is incredibly pricey.  Gasoline is taxed til it costs twice what it does in America.  On top of that, most people buy their cars through used-car dealers, rather than from private individuals. (You can get deals at yahoo.co.jp's auction site, though.) Still worse, there are incredibly high yearly car-taxes, and a gov't car inspection done once every 2 years (called a &quot;shakken&quot;).<br>
To avoid these expenses, try to buy a scooter or a motorbike of less than 250cc.  The cost-savings for those are significant, and they don't need &quot;shakken&quot;.<br>
====<br>
Refreshingly cheap:<br>
Supermarket stuff, and McDonal'ds/&quot;family restaurants&quot;/any fast food joint.  Also, surprisingly, fast food joints are low-class in America, but in Japan they don't carry that stigma.<br>
<br>
Japanese people DON'T TIP.  Cabs, restaurants, and haircutters are therefore quite a bit more expensive than their American counterparts.<br>
======<br>
Before you come to Japan, STOCK UP.  If your shoe or shirt size is average-to-large, you will have alot of difficulty finding your size in Japan.  I get my stuff sent by a friend in Hawaii, yet I'm only size 10.5/11 shoe.  Buy ALOT of deodorant before you come here, because a lifetime diet of hamburgers has made your body-chemistry significantly different (and stinkier) than an Asian's.  Consequently, deodorant in Japan is weak stuff, nearly useless to us.  Buy extra, and use it as a gift to foreigners you meet in Japan.  (We're always desperate for the stuff !)<br>
<br>
Get an international driver's license from the Automobile Association of America, before you come to Japan.  It's good for quite a while in Japan, and the Japanese driver's test is infamously difficult.  You can get an application for one over the internet, or from a travel agency.  Cost is about $15.  Provide 2 passport style photos, and a copy of the front and back of your driver's license. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sethness>SethNess</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.fureai-ch.ne.jp/~seth/clearhappy.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/14/03 6:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1227.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> living and working in Japan</span><hr size=1> My buddy was just trying to do the job he'd done back in Holland:  blacksmithing, cutlery, and wood-sculpting.  Keep in mind that he had certifications from world-class blacksmiths, including his father, who was the blacksmith for the Royal Family of Holland.  Also keep in mind that his craft was considerably different from Japanese-style blacksmithing, which probably made his getting an art-career work-visa a bit easier than for sketchers like you and me.<br>
